e continually reshaped by fierce internal tensions, bold and eccentric personalities, and shifting political circumstances.Matt Zwolinski and John Tomasi trace the history of libertarianism from its origins as a radical progressive ideology in the 1850s to its crisis of identity today. They examine the doctrine’s evolution through six defining themes: private property, skepticism of authority, free markets, individualism, spontaneous order, and individual liberty. They show how the movement took a turn toward conservativism during the Cold War, when the dangers of communism at home and abroad came to dominate libertarian thinking. Zwolinski and Tomasi reveal a history that is wider, more diverse, and more contentious than many of us realize.A groundbreaking work of scholarship, The Individualists uncovers the neglected roots of a movement that has championed the poor and marginalized since its founding, but whose talk of equal liberty has often been bent to serve the interests of the rich and powerful.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aLibertarianism. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Libertarianism .2bisacsh  aA Treatise of Human Nature.  aActivism.  aAdvocacy.  aAnalogy.  aAndrew Carnegie.  aAyn Rand and the World She Made.  aBarriers to entry.  aBeatrice Webb.  aBissau.  aBolivia.  aCape Verde.  aCapitalism.  aClassical liberalism.  aCollectivism.  aCompulsory sterilization.  aComstock laws.  aContagious Diseases Acts.  aCreative work.  aCrime.  aCurrency.  aEconomic freedom.  aEdward Atkinson (activist).  aExecutive agency.  aFraud.  aFree Market Fairness.  aGuaranteed minimum income.  aHeterosexism.  aImperialism.  aIndividual.  aIndividualism.  aIndividualist anarchism.  aInstitution.  aInternational isolation.  aInvisible hand.  aJi